      <abstract>
        <p>Kathleen Durkin letter on Roxana Robinson's June 3 essay about world literature and cab drivers</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>I read with great enjoyment the article by Roxana Robinson about world literature and cab drivers (''The Novelist and the Curious Cabbie,'' New York Observed, June 3). The combination of New York City cab drivers and a discussion of great literature is priceless.</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>I read with great enjoyment the article by Roxana Robinson about world literature and cab drivers (''The Novelist and the Curious Cabbie,'' New York Observed, June 3). The combination of New York City cab drivers and a discussion of great literature is priceless.</p>
        <p>This is also one of the great joys of living in New York City.</p>
        <p>I have met wonderful cabdrivers and learned a great deal about the world from them. Many discussions have been eye-opening about their countries, cultures, religions, family life and much more.</p>
        <p>Often, these encounters make my day.</p>
        <p>Wouldn't live anywhere else; this is one reason.</p>
        <p>Kathleen Durkin  Chelsea</p>
      </block>
